<h2>Egg Gate Zone and the Mecha Sonic Boss Fight</h2>

The demo's single zone, <strong>Egg Gate</strong>, is split into two acts and a boss encounter. Act 1 is a high-velocity assault on Eggman's fortress featuring loops, free-fall sections, breakable walls, and Tails cooperating from the Tornado. The level runs <strong>6+ minutes even on a speedrun</strong>, which gives you an idea of how much content is packed in.

<strong>Act 2 is entirely dedicated to the boss fight against Mecha Sonic</strong> — a character not seen as a major antagonist since Sonic 3 & Knuckles. The fight has multiple phases: it starts with standard attack patterns where you look for openings, then Mecha Sonic becomes increasingly aggressive with <strong>missile barrages and devastating laser attacks</strong> that fill a charge meter before firing. In the final phase, visibly damaged, Mecha Sonic becomes vulnerable to boost attacks. The battle ends with a Double Boost sequence and rapid button mashing for the finishing blow — and the stage continues even after the boss goes down.

<h2>Ring System and Ranking</h2>

Sonic Definitive introduces a <strong>leveling system tied directly to your ring count</strong>. The more rings you hold, the higher your level — but taking hits and losing rings drops you back down. Unlike most Sonic games, <strong>you don't lose all your rings from a single hit</strong>, which keeps the system from feeling punishing. Your ring count also affects Sonic's speed: more rings means faster movement.

The <strong>ranking system builds from the bottom up</strong>, and it's possible to earn an S rank even after losing a bunch of rings, as long as your total score stays high. Dying, however, will almost certainly knock you out of S rank territory. The system rewards aggressive, continuous play over cautious ring-hoarding.

<h2>Things Worth Knowing</h2>

This is a demo, and it shows in a few areas. <strong>The menu has noticeable input lag</strong> (though the gameplay itself runs fine), and Sonic's controls, while functional, occasionally feel stiff — a known limitation of the Clickteam Fusion engine. The <strong>homing attack can sometimes fail to connect</strong>, and Sonic doesn't always turn around when jumping, leading to the occasional unfair hit. The animated cutscenes are still unfinished — no color or effects yet — but they already add personality to the experience.

The sheer density of mechanics is both a strength and a potential concern. Everything works well within this demo's scope, but some fans have wondered whether the volume of systems (boost, stomp, air dash, slide, spin dash, super spin dash, special attack, light speed dash, QTEs, letter collection, ring leveling) might feel overwhelming in a longer game. For now, though, it all comes together in one of the most impressive SAGE 2025 demos available.

